04:16.488 --> 04:19.555
T.A.O., sonar, nothing on subsurface.

04:19.581 --> 04:21.898
Roger that.

04:48.414 --> 04:50.724
Oliver: [Laughing] I
can't take this anymore.

04:50.749 --> 04:52.279
- Max: No, you got to listen.
- Stop, stop.

04:52.304 --> 04:53.489
- You got to listen.
- No, stop.

04:53.514 --> 04:55.473
Stop, I can't. So the first
mate says to the judge,

04:55.499 --> 04:58.917
"I'll have you know, a sailor I am not."

04:58.942 --> 04:59.908
[Laughs]

04:59.933 --> 05:00.966
Oi!

05:01.331 --> 05:03.161
Anything on that destroyer?

05:03.186 --> 05:04.519
- No, mate.
- Come on.

05:04.545 --> 05:06.263
Quiet as a church mouse.

05:06.288 --> 05:09.716
Just 'cause the boss is off
ship ain't no excuse to lollygag.

05:09.741 --> 05:11.380
- Keep looking.
- All right.

05:11.828 --> 05:13.630
- Ned wants results.
- Yeah, all right.

05:13.655 --> 05:16.230
Don't "all right" me.

05:16.255 --> 05:19.317
I'm a goddamned warrant officer, class 2.

05:19.342 --> 05:21.926
Aye, sir.

05:21.965 --> 05:23.681
With his knickers in a twist.

05:23.706 --> 05:24.788
Shut it!

05:24.813 --> 05:26.813
[Laughs]

05:29.870 --> 05:32.538
Alisha: It must have
transmitted to the satellite

05:32.563 --> 05:33.596
right before the attack.

05:33.621 --> 05:34.877
Have you watched it?

05:34.902 --> 05:37.807
Only long enough to know
that it was for you, ma'am.

05:37.847 --> 05:40.510
But even from what I saw...

05:41.359 --> 05:43.576
It wasn't easy to watch.

05:45.145 --> 05:46.929
[Beep]

05:46.954 --> 05:48.671
[ <i> Rapid gunfire</i> ]

05:48.696 --> 05:52.497
<i>Rachel, oh, God, I
pray this gets to you.</i>

05:52.522 --> 05:55.871
<i>Listen, we're... We're
under attack, Rachel,</i>

05:55.896 --> 05:57.028
<i>but it's important... </i>

05:57.053 --> 05:58.970
<i>It's important that you learn this.</i>

05:58.995 --> 06:01.662
<i>I've been working with the data
you sent me about the cure.</i>

06:01.687 --> 06:03.187
<i>And I think I found a way to help.</i>

06:03.212 --> 06:04.541
[ <i> Rapid gunfire</i> ]

06:04.566 --> 06:06.841
<i>Using what I learned about
the measles project... </i>

06:06.866 --> 06:09.150
<i>Now, I know you think
that's crazy, but it works.</i>

06:09.175 --> 06:12.409
<i>I'm sending you the
data now. It's here.</i>

06:12.434 --> 06:14.448
- <i>Look, I don't... </i>
- [ <i> Banging</i> ]

06:14.473 --> 06:15.555
<i>Oh, God.</i>

06:15.580 --> 06:18.146
<i>Listen, Rachel.</i>

06:18.171 --> 06:21.338
<i>It's all worked out. All
you have to do is... </i>

06:21.363 --> 06:23.776
<i>I just somehow pray that
this file gets to you,</i>

06:23.801 --> 06:26.151
<i>that you get it off
the server, Rachel.</i>

06:26.176 --> 06:27.901
- MacDowell: <i> Okay.</i>
- <i>Got to know that... </i>

06:27.926 --> 06:30.205
- <i>Rachel.</i>
- [ <i> Clattering</i> ]

06:30.230 --> 06:33.106
<i>Come on, now. Take it all.</i>

06:33.131 --> 06:34.664
<i>We need to find that server.</i>

06:34.689 --> 06:36.406
<i>Okay, doc.</i>

06:36.431 --> 06:37.797
- <i>No.
- Stand up.</i>

06:37.822 --> 06:39.221
<i>Please. Please.</i>

06:39.246 --> 06:41.641
[ <i> Gunshots</i> ]

06:43.607 --> 06:47.042
Slattery: Well, that's how they
were able to get the locations

06:47.067 --> 06:48.317
of all the labs.

06:48.342 --> 06:49.947
Stole them from Dr. Hunter.

06:50.152 --> 06:53.487
He was working on an experiment

06:53.512 --> 06:56.513
to turn my liquid injectable
version of the cure

06:56.538 --> 07:01.033
into a powder so it could be
released over populated areas

07:01.058 --> 07:05.777
via helicopters, planes, drones, even.

07:05.882 --> 07:08.683
I could manufacture a
highly concentrated powder

07:08.708 --> 07:10.207
right here on the ship.

07:10.232 --> 07:12.066
We wouldn't even need labs anymore.

07:12.245 --> 07:14.028
So people could breathe in the cure.

07:14.053 --> 07:16.025
It would be very much like crop-dusting.

07:16.050 --> 07:19.626
Mass inoculations without
glassware, needles,

07:19.651 --> 07:21.347
all the infrastructure
that we no longer have.

07:21.372 --> 07:23.256
Do you think Hunter was
actually able to do it?

07:23.635 --> 07:25.602
I know that he had some good results

07:25.627 --> 07:27.168
aerosolizing the measles vaccine,

07:27.193 --> 07:30.077
but I won't know until we get
down to his lab in Florida.

07:30.102 --> 07:32.186
The formulas are locked
away on his computers.

07:32.211 --> 07:33.766
Absolutely not.

07:33.791 --> 07:35.116
It's a long shot,

07:35.141 --> 07:37.258
and we've got bigger fish to fry right now.

07:37.584 --> 07:39.283
Really?

07:39.308 --> 07:41.950
Bigger fish?

07:42.496 --> 07:45.047
And by that, I assume you mean revenge.

07:45.072 --> 07:46.636
By that, I mean we're not going anywhere

07:46.661 --> 07:48.336
until we take out that sub.

07:51.657 --> 07:53.440
The men who killed Hunter, their accent...

07:53.465 --> 07:55.215
That was Irish, right?

07:57.497 --> 07:58.879
Yes.

07:58.946 --> 08:01.496
Means the sub commander
has people on the ground.

08:01.521 --> 08:04.489
<i>Achilles</i> was 200 miles
offshore when it launched on the labs.

08:04.514 --> 08:06.824
No way they were able to slip
back and forth between Florida.

08:06.849 --> 08:09.524
Dr. Hunter's lab location was
hidden on the secure server.

08:09.549 --> 08:11.716
The bastards never got the
flash drive from their man.

08:11.786 --> 08:13.953
- So how'd they find it?
- It doesn't matter.

08:14.605 --> 08:17.727
Whoever killed your
friend is long gone by now.

08:17.752 --> 08:19.201
This is a wild goose chase.

08:19.226 --> 08:21.727
If all you care about is...

08:25.193 --> 08:28.166
Have you forgotten what
we're all doing here?

08:30.480 --> 08:33.782
Find the cure, save the world.

08:33.807 --> 08:35.857
Remember?

08:54.312 --> 08:56.529
Clear.

09:03.455 --> 09:07.690
Pilot: There's a TAC
headed to the east wing.

09:07.726 --> 09:10.627
<i>Nathan James,</i> Sabrehawk
One leaving the landing zone.

09:10.662 --> 09:11.628
Vulture Team in place.

09:11.663 --> 09:13.329
Roger, Sabrehawk One.

09:25.677 --> 09:28.011
[Door closes]

09:28.063 --> 09:30.396
[Insects buzzing]

09:34.675 --> 09:36.299
Clear.

09:37.856 --> 09:39.355
Clear.

09:42.114 --> 09:45.749
Wolf: More dead doctors in the east wing.

09:49.212 --> 09:52.919
<i>Nathan James,</i> Vulture Team.

09:52.954 --> 09:55.254
We got what we expected.

09:56.173 --> 09:59.341
Roger, Vulture Team.

10:05.935 --> 10:07.484
[Sighs]

10:23.420 --> 10:25.230
He was a giant.

10:25.779 --> 10:28.269
The smartest man I knew.

10:29.518 --> 10:32.202
Cruz: Ma'am, they shot up the
doctor's office pretty good.

10:32.227 --> 10:34.077
Bashed the computers to bits.

10:34.285 --> 10:36.118
I'm so sorry.

10:37.424 --> 10:39.851
[Sighs]

10:40.173 --> 10:42.473
[Sniffs]

10:46.690 --> 10:49.211
I found these cultures.

10:51.067 --> 10:54.340
So at least we can continue
making the cure for now.

10:57.718 --> 11:01.916
See if there's anything
in that box to help.

11:06.578 --> 11:08.661
Did you find anything
that links to the sub?

11:08.696 --> 11:11.809
Aside from how good these
guys are at killing? No, sir.

11:11.956 --> 11:13.988
Sir, they came in quiet.

11:14.013 --> 11:15.118
Cut the lock at the north gate.

11:15.120 --> 11:16.512
But they left in a hurry

11:16.537 --> 11:18.037
and drove right over the flattened fence.

11:18.072 --> 11:19.572
There are muddy tracks to follow.

11:19.624 --> 11:21.551
Sir, may I speak freely?

11:21.576 --> 11:22.741
Always.

11:22.777 --> 11:24.493
Let's go.

11:26.531 --> 11:29.031
Sir, we'll take Dr. Scott
back to <i> Nathan James</i>

11:29.083 --> 11:31.453
so she can finish her
important work. Come with us.

11:31.478 --> 11:33.659
Whoever did this may have
already swept through Europe,

11:33.684 --> 11:36.148
and we cannot allow them to
get a foothold here in America,

11:36.207 --> 11:38.734
and we can't keep looking
over our shoulder for that sub.

11:38.853 --> 11:40.903
We find them, we make it safe

11:40.928 --> 11:42.781
for Dr. Scott to finish her work.

11:42.806 --> 11:44.554
This is all the same mission now.

11:44.579 --> 11:45.828
Fair enough.

11:45.853 --> 11:48.854
But I can see it in your eyes, sir...

11:48.879 --> 11:50.713
Your desire for vengeance.

11:50.738 --> 11:51.883
So I'm asking,

11:51.908 --> 11:55.969
as a man who is never more
than 509 feet from his captain,

11:55.994 --> 11:59.016
don't let this sub become your white whale.

12:01.566 --> 12:03.365
Miller! Cruz!

12:03.392 --> 12:04.745
Aye, sir.

12:04.770 --> 12:07.271
Go with the master chief, get
Dr. Scott back to the ship.

12:07.296 --> 12:08.440
The rest of you with me.

12:08.465 --> 12:10.320
Chief Taylor, find us a vehicle.

12:10.345 --> 12:11.544
We need to follow those tracks.

12:11.569 --> 12:14.435
Yes, sir. Let's go.

12:17.374 --> 12:19.755
[Camera shutter clicks]

12:22.920 --> 12:27.890
When you find the people
who did this, captain...

12:34.982 --> 12:37.900
Kill them.

12:48.323 --> 12:50.790
Taylor: Captain, take a look.

13:23.869 --> 13:26.736
One trail ends, the other begins.

13:26.761 --> 13:29.961
Let's see if these boats can
take us where we need to go.

13:45.252 --> 13:47.886
<i>Nathan James,</i> Vulture Team. Over.

13:47.911 --> 13:49.660
Read you loud and clear,
Vulture Team. Over.

13:49.685 --> 13:53.487
We're approximately
29.23 north, 81.55 west.

13:53.512 --> 13:57.510
Requesting U.A.V. flyover
our whiskey with FLIR package.

13:57.535 --> 14:00.626
I want a full sweep,
50-nautical-mile radius.

14:00.651 --> 14:02.066
These guys are hiding in the swamps.

14:02.091 --> 14:03.924
I need you to find them. Over.

14:03.949 --> 14:06.179
Roger, Vulture Team.

14:12.413 --> 14:14.196
All right?

14:14.198 --> 14:15.748
No.

14:15.783 --> 14:18.167
[Door closes, bicycle bell rings]

14:18.202 --> 14:19.418
Hey.

14:19.453 --> 14:21.120
[Sniffs]

14:21.172 --> 14:23.455
Sean: Well? I love this town.

14:23.507 --> 14:27.305
Everything you hear about
Southern hospitality, it's true.

14:27.330 --> 14:30.283
I met some very kind people.

14:30.308 --> 14:32.191
Uh, they gave me sweet tea.

14:32.216 --> 14:35.690
I had this little chat
with the local sheriff.

14:35.715 --> 14:37.715
He says to me, he goes,

14:38.027 --> 14:40.645
"we're all in this together."

14:40.670 --> 14:42.169
[Laughs]

14:42.194 --> 14:43.503
It's funny, no?

14:43.671 --> 14:45.504
Yeah, I'll bet.

14:45.664 --> 14:47.798
How long till they're all dead?

14:47.887 --> 14:49.533
Well, I'm still quite contagious,

14:49.558 --> 14:52.245
so, you know, won't be long now.

14:53.203 --> 14:56.705
Out of the ashes, a few will rise.

14:56.730 --> 14:58.763
Our army will grow.

14:58.788 --> 15:01.327
Brilliant. Brilliant.

15:01.352 --> 15:02.601
You see, Ned?

15:02.626 --> 15:05.446
Do you understand what
we have here in Niels?

15:05.957 --> 15:07.540
Oh, Ned.

15:07.565 --> 15:09.061
I passed a department store,

15:09.086 --> 15:10.608
and I was thinking that, like,

15:10.633 --> 15:12.358
maybe you and some of your friends

15:12.383 --> 15:13.710
could get some fresh clothes,

15:13.794 --> 15:17.760
improve the smell on the submarine, maybe?

15:17.881 --> 15:20.014
[Glass shatters]

15:20.410 --> 15:21.876
Do you know what I think, Sean?!

15:22.099 --> 15:23.982
I think this is a dodge!

15:24.018 --> 15:25.858
I think it's an excuse

15:25.883 --> 15:28.485
to duck out of your
responsibilities at home!

15:28.572 --> 15:30.499
You're afraid!

15:30.657 --> 15:33.024
You are afraid to lead!

15:33.143 --> 15:36.311
You are afraid of that destroyer!

15:36.497 --> 15:40.783
And that's why we're stuck
on this bleeding rock!

15:51.107 --> 15:53.491
Say that again, Bruv.

15:55.396 --> 15:58.814
Tell me I'm afraid.

16:04.525 --> 16:08.728
I am culling the herd, Ned.

16:09.005 --> 16:12.006
And the pure will have a chance to join us.

16:12.031 --> 16:14.960
Those who refuse my beneficence will die

16:14.985 --> 16:17.035
along with the crew of that Navy ship.

16:17.060 --> 16:20.561
Now, you have a choice to make.

16:20.624 --> 16:23.826
Do you want to help me?

16:25.561 --> 16:30.505
Or do you want to join our
beloved mother in the grave?

16:35.297 --> 16:38.014
Well...

16:38.039 --> 16:40.874
Now you've come to mention it...

16:41.671 --> 16:44.783
Do you think Beyoncé's immune?

16:45.432 --> 16:46.732
Eh?

16:48.058 --> 16:50.826
I mean, it's possible.

16:50.851 --> 16:52.985
5% and all that.

16:54.214 --> 16:56.674
I think she'd look rather good on my arm.

16:56.699 --> 16:58.031
[Chuckles]

16:58.056 --> 17:00.426
Don't you think?

17:00.507 --> 17:02.624
[Switchblade clicks]

17:02.649 --> 17:06.425
[Laughs] Ned.

17:26.093 --> 17:28.307
The nearest big city is St. Augustine,

17:28.332 --> 17:29.385
but they're dark.

17:29.410 --> 17:30.925
If it were me, I'd head inland.

17:30.950 --> 17:32.639
Yeah, but north or south?

17:32.828 --> 17:34.461
That's the question.

17:34.574 --> 17:37.709
Sir, U.A.V. At 5,000 feet,

17:37.734 --> 17:40.354
30 miles north of Vulture Team.

17:43.587 --> 17:45.754
Nothing for miles.

17:45.929 --> 17:47.462
In Th... In those swamps,

17:47.487 --> 17:49.003
you'd think we'd get a heat signature

17:49.028 --> 17:51.862
off an alligator or something.

17:51.887 --> 17:54.088
Nah, gators are cold-blooded.

17:54.936 --> 17:56.302
In Florida heat, they'd look

17:56.327 --> 17:58.437
about as warm as the ground around 'em.

17:58.922 --> 18:00.237
Right.

18:00.262 --> 18:01.428
Sorry, sir.

18:01.453 --> 18:03.384
We don't have too many
gators where I'm from.

18:03.409 --> 18:05.756
Yeah, well, my son taught me that.

18:05.781 --> 18:07.197
He hated school,

18:07.222 --> 18:10.337
but he knew <i> everything</i>
about animals and dinosaurs.

18:10.362 --> 18:12.548
- [Rapid beeping]
- Nishioka: Got something, sir.

18:12.573 --> 18:13.370
Pretty high.

18:13.395 --> 18:16.562
Could be generators, people,
maybe a large campground.

18:16.587 --> 18:19.038
[Radio chatter]

18:19.558 --> 18:21.469
Slattery: Nothing else for miles.

18:23.254 --> 18:25.705
Vulture Team, we have a target.

18:25.730 --> 18:27.939
U.A.V.'s picking up a large heat signature

18:27.964 --> 18:29.930
about 23 miles north of your whiskey.

18:29.955 --> 18:34.707
30.136 north, 81.678 west.

18:34.732 --> 18:36.315
These are our guys.

18:36.340 --> 18:37.555
It's got to be.

18:37.791 --> 18:40.041
Only people within this boat's range.

18:40.066 --> 18:42.261
<i>Nathan James,</i> Vulture Team.

18:42.286 --> 18:44.369
We're en route. Will advise.

18:44.394 --> 18:46.270
- Roger that.
- Let's move out!

19:12.803 --> 19:16.845
I need to turn our liquid
vaccine into an aerosol form.

19:16.870 --> 19:19.592
And to do so, I need
the proper chemical base

19:19.625 --> 19:20.632
to cut with our vaccine

19:20.657 --> 19:23.234
to create a stable and dry formulation.

19:23.259 --> 19:25.292
Something that won't degrade its potency.

19:25.545 --> 19:28.580
Powder base brings with it
all kinds of complications.

19:28.609 --> 19:31.506
Which is why no one's been able to do it.

19:32.331 --> 19:35.357
It's utterly organic, completely simple.

19:35.382 --> 19:38.700
Missing just enough pieces
to drive us crazy solving it.

19:39.104 --> 19:42.093
It's the same shape as cyclohexane,

19:42.145 --> 19:43.845
a dry-cleaning solvent.

19:43.870 --> 19:45.404
It's way too toxic.

19:45.429 --> 19:47.145
I have to ask.

19:47.170 --> 19:49.033
Is it... Is it possible

19:49.058 --> 19:51.592
that Dr. Hunter never solved it himself?

19:54.375 --> 19:55.758
No.

19:55.783 --> 19:58.208
He solved it.

19:58.529 --> 20:00.729
He gave his life to tell me.

20:17.495 --> 20:20.804
Green, Taylor, Tex,
take the southern flank.

20:20.829 --> 20:22.166
Lieutenant Burk, Lieutenant Bivas,

20:22.191 --> 20:24.347
you're coming with me... we'll
circle around from the north.

20:24.372 --> 20:27.239
- Aye, sir.
- Let's move.

20:30.064 --> 20:33.947
[Indistinct conversations in distance]

20:46.586 --> 20:49.254
Some kind of safe zone, captain.

20:54.730 --> 20:57.448
[Truck approaching]

20:57.473 --> 20:59.473
[Brakes squeal]

20:59.498 --> 21:02.399
[Engine shuts off, door opens]

21:13.793 --> 21:17.178
[Radio chatter]

21:20.068 --> 21:21.817
<i>Sì, sì. Ho capito. Sì.</i>

21:21.842 --> 21:23.308
<i>Dove sei Ora? Sei vicino?</i>

21:23.333 --> 21:24.578
[Radio chatter]

21:24.578 --> 21:26.398
<i>Sì sono Io... </i>

21:26.960 --> 21:31.576
<i>Sì lo sono. Arriverò... il
... .. più presto possibile.</i>

21:36.034 --> 21:38.468
It's not just a safe zone.

21:38.493 --> 21:41.244
There's at least a few mercs
from the <i> Solace</i> here.

21:41.269 --> 21:43.602
And they're talking to the sub right now.

21:43.627 --> 21:46.545
I say again, they are
communicating with the sub.

21:46.576 --> 21:48.914
Roger, Vulture Team.
They're talking to the sub.

21:48.916 --> 21:50.576
That means they're at
radio depth. Find them.

21:50.601 --> 21:51.723
Aye, sir. Searching.

21:51.752 --> 21:53.668
Can you make out what they're saying?

21:53.693 --> 21:56.523
Definitely radio communication,
sir, but it's encrypted.

21:56.548 --> 21:57.968
Okay, you know the drill.

21:57.993 --> 21:59.993
Yes, sir. Starting decryption now.

22:00.018 --> 22:02.296
I see three mercs on the inside,

22:02.321 --> 22:04.500
another two behind the shed.

22:04.525 --> 22:06.775
- We can take them.
- No, we wait.

22:06.800 --> 22:08.682
Let's see where they lead us.

22:26.077 --> 22:28.161
[Sighs]

22:31.706 --> 22:33.706
Uh, ma'am, I thought you might be hungry.

22:34.326 --> 22:36.386
How very thoughtful of you.

22:36.411 --> 22:39.351
Chicken and mushroom in a roux sauce...

22:39.376 --> 22:41.576
- My specialty.
- Is that right?

22:41.601 --> 22:43.884
It's good enough for the President
of the United States, so...

22:44.135 --> 22:47.640
You prepared food for the president?

22:47.665 --> 22:49.359
At Camp David.

22:49.451 --> 22:52.572
It was his favorite dish, or so I'm told.

22:52.597 --> 22:54.049
- You're having me on.
- No.

22:54.073 --> 22:55.206
[Laughs] No, ma'am.

22:55.231 --> 22:56.716
Only the best Navy cooks

22:56.741 --> 22:58.490
get to cook for the commander in chief.

22:58.515 --> 23:00.882
Why in heaven would you leave that job?

23:00.907 --> 23:04.041
You got to go to sea if
you want to make rank.

23:05.156 --> 23:08.117
You know, it's an art
preparing the perfect roux,

23:08.142 --> 23:09.892
especially seeing how hard it is

23:09.927 --> 23:12.119
to get fresh ingredients these days.

23:12.144 --> 23:16.363
You see, the real secret is
sifting the flour just right.

23:16.388 --> 23:17.954
Too heavy, and the minute
it hits that butter,

23:17.979 --> 23:19.587
you got yourself a fritter.

23:19.612 --> 23:20.759
But you do it right,

23:20.784 --> 23:25.861
man, you got yourself a nice, rich sauce.

23:25.886 --> 23:28.887
Not too soupy, not too thick.

23:31.342 --> 23:33.770
Oh, my God.

23:34.866 --> 23:36.313
It's completely delicious.

23:36.338 --> 23:39.770
Oh, ma'am, you haven't even tried it.

23:40.208 --> 23:42.322
I need a food base.

23:42.347 --> 23:43.680
If I can isolate it

23:43.705 --> 23:45.900
and have it adhere to the vaccine

23:45.925 --> 23:48.809
and form the micro powder...

23:49.034 --> 23:51.034
Thank you, Bacon.

23:51.059 --> 23:52.559
- Thank you!
- Uh...

23:52.957 --> 23:55.243
So, you ain't even gonna taste it?

23:55.268 --> 23:57.868
- Boy: Kick it!
- Oh, come on!

23:57.893 --> 24:00.477
- Oh! Great save!
- Yeah!

24:00.502 --> 24:02.386
Yeah, he scores!

24:02.411 --> 24:03.877
Give me something, brother.

24:03.902 --> 24:06.069
That was fun, guys. Thanks.

24:10.495 --> 24:12.999
Hey, thanks for the stuff. Appreciate it.

24:13.024 --> 24:15.400
Thanks very much. Appreciate it.

24:16.263 --> 24:19.600
That's fun, thanks.
Hey, Doll, how you doing?

24:26.906 --> 24:30.415
Hey, man. They are a friendly group.

24:30.447 --> 24:33.814
Handing out clothes, food, blankets.

24:33.839 --> 24:35.822
It's an apocalyptic love-in.

24:35.862 --> 24:38.259
All that's missing is
music and some wacky weed.

24:38.284 --> 24:40.290
- Americans?
- Every one of 'em.

24:40.315 --> 24:41.982
No sign of no foreign fighters.

24:42.007 --> 24:42.703
[Vehicle approaches]

24:42.728 --> 24:43.694
[Rifle cocks]

24:43.719 --> 24:45.469
[Engine shuts off]

24:45.494 --> 24:47.494
[Doors close]

24:47.519 --> 24:49.111
Where'd you find that?

24:49.266 --> 24:51.683
Commandeered by order of the Navy.

24:51.708 --> 24:54.243
Wolf: Couple of late
arrivals from out of town.

24:54.268 --> 24:55.601
No one will miss them, sir.

24:55.626 --> 24:57.543
Captain, it's looking like a company move.

24:57.568 --> 24:59.642
They're loading up the trucks
and heading out over there.

24:59.667 --> 25:02.018
Ravit: Same here. Buses arriving.

25:02.043 --> 25:03.459
They're frisking people.

25:03.484 --> 25:05.549
Now we got a ride. Let's follow.

25:05.574 --> 25:08.181
Even in civilian clothes,
we're gonna stand out.

25:08.416 --> 25:09.915
We need to split up.

25:10.264 --> 25:15.080
Green, Taylor, Tex, take
the truck and our gear.

25:15.105 --> 25:16.377
Follow the convoy.

25:16.402 --> 25:18.902
Ravit, Burk, come with me.

25:19.358 --> 25:22.193
We're taking the last bus out of here.

25:22.218 --> 25:25.408
<i>Nathan James,</i>
we're going radio silent.

25:25.440 --> 25:27.424
Negative, Vulture Team. Do not go dark.

25:27.449 --> 25:29.026
Keep contact through green and Taylor.

25:29.051 --> 25:31.315
I say again, do not go dark.

25:31.340 --> 25:32.909
We got a lead, X.O.

25:33.020 --> 25:35.271
Need to follow it. I say...

25:35.296 --> 25:37.213
Chief Taylor, you're now our rally point

25:37.238 --> 25:39.385
and our way out of whatever
trouble we get into.

25:39.410 --> 25:42.294
Aye, sir. I've got your back.

25:42.873 --> 25:44.706
Burk: Sir?

25:45.101 --> 25:47.067
Ditching our gear and our weapons...

25:47.092 --> 25:49.509
You sure about this?

25:50.041 --> 25:52.417
Roger that.

25:59.827 --> 26:02.143
Take off your clothes.

26:35.073 --> 26:38.690
[Indistinct conversations]

26:49.222 --> 26:51.589
Janine: Everybody I knew is dead.

26:51.614 --> 26:54.449
My husband, my children...

26:54.474 --> 26:56.545
Four girls.

26:56.928 --> 26:58.761
I'm sorry.

26:58.825 --> 27:00.625
Don't be.

27:00.650 --> 27:02.817
I'm sure you've got your stories.

27:03.900 --> 27:06.446
I lost my wife.

27:07.988 --> 27:09.988
And then you found us.

27:10.382 --> 27:13.016
I-in my case, they found me.

27:13.041 --> 27:16.646
I was just out wandering,
no place to call home.

27:16.671 --> 27:20.807
I didn't even know
there was others like us.

27:20.832 --> 27:24.884
How many are there like us?

27:25.051 --> 27:27.268
Sean says there are millions.

27:27.293 --> 27:29.126
Sean?

27:29.151 --> 27:32.485
Have you heard him speak?
You seen the videos?

27:32.510 --> 27:34.176
Oh, you have to.

27:34.201 --> 27:36.902
And, I mean, don't you let that
fancy accent of his fool you.

27:37.114 --> 27:41.349
I mean, he's European and
all, but he's just like us.

27:41.374 --> 27:42.873
I'd like to meet him.

27:43.094 --> 27:44.427
Well, it's your lucky day,

27:53.910 --> 27:57.528
I need to separate the myoinositol.

27:57.588 --> 28:00.039
Milowsky: Are you sure you
have the correct stereoisomer?

28:00.064 --> 28:02.145
I suggest we try a corn base.

28:02.170 --> 28:04.067
Because of the phytic acid?

28:04.102 --> 28:06.496
Myo is geometrically more stable,

28:06.521 --> 28:08.698
but chelation of the phytic acid

28:08.723 --> 28:12.225
could prevent mineral absorption
into the vaccine structure.

28:12.250 --> 28:14.583
Worth a shot.

28:14.833 --> 28:16.022
Bacon?

28:16.524 --> 28:17.874
Uh...

28:17.899 --> 28:19.899
I'm... I'm sorry, ma'am.

28:19.924 --> 28:22.207
I-I'm afraid you lost me.

28:22.232 --> 28:25.685
At what point, exactly, did I lose you?

28:25.710 --> 28:27.843
About two hours ago.

28:28.661 --> 28:31.496
Well, let's start with the flour, shall we?

28:45.382 --> 28:47.549
We're headed north.

28:47.574 --> 28:49.349
I have a visual of the bus convoy.

28:49.374 --> 28:51.321
I believe Charlie Oscar's in the last bus.

28:51.347 --> 28:52.892
Roger, Cobra Team.

28:52.917 --> 28:54.931
Sir, the sub is transmitting.

28:54.956 --> 28:57.123
They're communicating with someone on land.

28:57.148 --> 28:59.002
Still cannot break the encryption, sir,

28:59.027 --> 29:00.810
but I have a good read
on the signal bearing.

29:00.835 --> 29:02.585
How accurate?

29:02.610 --> 29:05.110
The sub appears to be
holding still at radio depth.

29:05.135 --> 29:06.009
They're not moving, sir.

29:06.034 --> 29:07.450
Mason, can you calculate a range?

29:07.475 --> 29:08.808
Yes, sir, this broadcast

29:08.833 --> 29:10.466
has a different point of origin on land.

29:10.491 --> 29:11.407
It's further north.

29:11.432 --> 29:13.538
We're triangulating approximate
location for the sub.

29:13.700 --> 29:15.316
90 nautical miles.

29:16.024 --> 29:19.313
Can't get much closer at quiet
one without tipping our hand.

29:19.595 --> 29:21.145
Nothing on passive sonar?

29:21.170 --> 29:22.420
Nothing, sir.

29:22.445 --> 29:24.273
She's quiet even at 30 knots,

29:24.298 --> 29:25.587
pretty much silent when she's not moving.

29:25.612 --> 29:27.519
Calculate a position on our target.

29:27.544 --> 29:29.173
I hold the sub at this location.

29:29.198 --> 29:33.304
<i>Nathan James</i> is
here, making 5 knots.

29:33.682 --> 29:35.407
We have a vector plot.

29:35.432 --> 29:37.439
At this range, here's our dog box.

29:37.464 --> 29:40.736
T.A.O., hostile sub designate as Goblin 1.

29:41.821 --> 29:44.271
Yeah, yeah. I'm here, I'm here, I'm here.

29:44.296 --> 29:46.130
How is it?

29:46.155 --> 29:47.423
Yeah, no, no, no, no.

29:47.448 --> 29:48.898
Forget about that.

29:48.923 --> 29:50.939
Have you found the American ship?

29:50.964 --> 29:53.052
Not yet, but we're
heading back towards you.

29:53.077 --> 29:54.056
Your brother said...

29:54.081 --> 29:56.915
I don't care what my
brother said, all right?

29:56.940 --> 29:58.767
We are gonna sink those bastards.

29:58.792 --> 30:00.345
Oi, yes, sir.

30:00.370 --> 30:03.878
Now, here's what I want you to do, okay?

30:04.048 --> 30:05.806
X.O., F.I.S. is green.

30:05.831 --> 30:08.465
Hold active sonar until we
have a solid track on the sub.

30:08.490 --> 30:10.407
Does the dog box cover the sub's location?

30:10.432 --> 30:12.515
Plenty big, ma'am... as long
as the sub is in that box,

30:12.540 --> 30:14.240
the ASROC torpedo will find it.

30:14.339 --> 30:16.228
Slattery: Okay, we only
get one shot at this.

30:16.253 --> 30:17.719
Once we go active,

30:17.744 --> 30:19.737
they'll know where we
are, then they fire back.

30:19.762 --> 30:21.974
T.A.O., permission to shine lance searcher.

30:21.999 --> 30:23.034
Shine lance searcher.

30:23.059 --> 30:24.803
Shining Lance searcher.

30:29.640 --> 30:32.607
Sonar, T.A.O., do you
have an active contact?

30:32.632 --> 30:34.539
I don't understand.

30:34.564 --> 30:39.039
All stations, sonar. Sonar
holds no active contact.

30:39.718 --> 30:41.888
- It's not a sub.
- What is it?

30:42.073 --> 30:44.146
The sonar signature shows
nothing in the water.

30:44.171 --> 30:46.677
Whatever is transmitting from
that spot is on the surface.

30:46.702 --> 30:48.641
It could be a radio relay, a buoy.

30:48.666 --> 30:50.287
That would explain why it's not moving.

30:50.312 --> 30:52.012
And that's how the sub is communicating

30:52.037 --> 30:53.053
with their people on land.

30:53.078 --> 30:54.878
Sub's using it to mask its location.

30:54.903 --> 30:57.383
We have a solid radar track
on the floating relay, sir.

30:57.408 --> 30:58.284
Okay.

30:58.463 --> 31:00.383
Very well.

31:00.467 --> 31:01.883
If we can't use it to find them,

31:01.908 --> 31:03.383
we can't decrypt what they're saying,

31:03.408 --> 31:04.584
let's not let 'em talk at all.

31:04.609 --> 31:05.576
Ready an SM-2.

31:05.608 --> 31:09.442
MSS. T.A.O., kill track 5025 with birds.

31:09.467 --> 31:13.553
Mss, aye. Kill track 5025 with bird.

31:14.123 --> 31:15.573
Fire.

31:15.598 --> 31:18.152
Bird is away.

31:23.052 --> 31:24.661
_

31:24.692 --> 31:27.131
Hello, Ned? Are you there, mate?

31:27.156 --> 31:28.355
Ned?

31:28.787 --> 31:30.451
Direct hit, ma'am.

31:30.476 --> 31:32.142
Radio signal's dead, sir.

31:32.902 --> 31:34.935
Hello?

31:35.795 --> 31:37.342
Oi!

31:37.367 --> 31:39.074
Ian!

31:40.161 --> 31:42.528
Is there anybody there?!

31:43.580 --> 31:45.163
Shit!

32:39.006 --> 32:40.673
Uh-oh.

32:40.698 --> 32:44.366
Looks like they're taking
us to the service entrance.

32:44.391 --> 32:46.508
Taylor, Cobra. We're splitting.

32:46.533 --> 32:48.233
Buses are headed to the main building.

32:49.003 --> 32:51.323
Find us a rally point.

32:51.348 --> 32:53.064
Roger.

32:59.011 --> 33:00.797
Here we go.

33:15.876 --> 33:18.577
Hey, master chief, any word?

33:19.656 --> 33:22.607
[Sighs] Three teams on
an undercover mission,

33:22.632 --> 33:24.610
wandering the swamps of central Florida

33:24.635 --> 33:28.053
led by my commanding
officer, alone and unafraid.

33:28.265 --> 33:29.765
Ma'am, I love the Navy,

33:29.790 --> 33:32.424
but I don't know if I'll
ever get used to this.

33:32.451 --> 33:33.983
I just pray they come back safe,

33:34.008 --> 33:35.958
and we get this vendetta behind us.

33:36.906 --> 33:39.274
They'll make it back.

33:39.299 --> 33:40.682
They always do.

33:40.718 --> 33:43.858
Find anything useful in Dr. Hunter's lab?

33:44.165 --> 33:45.814
Actually...

33:45.839 --> 33:48.006
What's that?

33:48.042 --> 33:49.374
[Blows]

33:50.310 --> 33:53.615
Cornstarch from the chief's mess.

33:53.640 --> 33:55.240
It turns out the secret ingredient

33:55.265 --> 33:56.481
that I've been looking for

33:56.506 --> 33:58.128
was being used to make pancakes.

33:58.153 --> 33:59.570
So you found it?

33:59.595 --> 34:01.127
Well, I have the recipe,

34:01.152 --> 34:02.569
and now all I need is to build

34:02.594 --> 34:04.544
a machine to manufacture the micro powder,

34:04.569 --> 34:07.937
so I was hoping that you
might be able to lend me

34:07.962 --> 34:10.889
one or two of your capable machinists?

34:10.914 --> 34:13.543
I think that can be arranged.

34:13.728 --> 34:15.813
Man: Hold up.

34:16.407 --> 34:18.810
Here we go.

34:22.132 --> 34:23.382
Howdy!

34:23.505 --> 34:24.587
Howdy?

34:24.612 --> 34:26.094
What? I'm from Connecticut.

34:26.120 --> 34:27.753
Hmm.

34:28.149 --> 34:30.483
Whereabouts you boys come from?

34:30.507 --> 34:32.454
Pompano Beach, baby.

34:32.478 --> 34:34.646
- Fancy pants!
- [Laughs]

34:34.670 --> 34:36.621
Well, come on. We got shit to do.

34:36.646 --> 34:38.896
Pull up around back.

34:40.474 --> 34:41.975
Pompano Beach?

34:42.000 --> 34:43.514
Nice pull.

34:43.540 --> 34:44.790
Well, I knew a gal

34:44.815 --> 34:46.398
had a houseboat on the intercoastal

34:46.422 --> 34:47.687
back in the late '90s.

34:47.942 --> 34:50.388
It was a hell of a winter.

34:52.797 --> 34:55.016
Man: Welcome to seaport marina, everyone.

34:55.042 --> 34:57.449
We got coffee, baked bread.

34:58.161 --> 35:00.148
Please, come on in.

35:00.268 --> 35:04.049
Got fresh, cool water
inside, plenty to eat.

35:04.074 --> 35:06.259
No sign of Danny or Tex.

35:06.284 --> 35:08.220
Armed guards every 100 yards.

35:08.245 --> 35:10.452
Barbed wire fences, roving sentries.

35:10.477 --> 35:11.653
It's like a fortress.

35:11.678 --> 35:13.153
Or a prison.

35:14.306 --> 35:16.673
Now, I'm sure there are those among you

35:16.698 --> 35:19.616
who say, "why fight?

35:19.967 --> 35:21.934
Why judge those who are not blessed

35:21.959 --> 35:23.748
with our purity of blood?"

35:23.773 --> 35:26.107
Well, I assure you, brothers and sisters,

35:26.610 --> 35:29.060
that we are not the ones
who brought this fight.

35:29.085 --> 35:30.273
- Woman: Yeah!
- Man: Right.

35:30.298 --> 35:31.255
[Applause]

35:31.280 --> 35:33.099
Our bodies are immune to the virus,

35:33.124 --> 35:34.333
but not to bigotry!

35:34.358 --> 35:36.108
[Cheers and applause]

35:36.133 --> 35:38.264
Not to hatred!

35:38.289 --> 35:40.206
You've all heard stories

35:40.231 --> 35:41.764
of immunes dragged from their homes...

35:41.789 --> 35:43.064
That voice.

35:43.209 --> 35:45.075
By their own neighbors.

35:45.100 --> 35:46.550
I recognize it.

35:46.575 --> 35:48.241
We have the responsibility
to protect ourselves...

35:48.266 --> 35:50.100
Video from Dr. Hunter's lab.

35:50.125 --> 35:52.364
To band together!

35:52.389 --> 35:54.764
These are the guys.

35:55.533 --> 35:58.663
For it is a fight, us against them!

35:58.688 --> 36:00.278
[Cheers and applause]

36:00.303 --> 36:04.722
Got themselves a cult...
With an army behind them.

36:04.747 --> 36:07.909
To fight for our immunity and
what we're trying to build here.

36:07.934 --> 36:09.903
- Can you do that for me?
- [Cheers and applause]

36:10.336 --> 36:11.585
Can you do that?

36:11.610 --> 36:14.527
Can you be a warrior for the cause?

36:14.552 --> 36:16.731
Cobra Team, what is your whiskey?

36:16.756 --> 36:18.099
This is Cobra Team.

36:18.124 --> 36:19.802
Tiger Team is out of sight

36:19.827 --> 36:21.509
behind the building complex.

36:21.534 --> 36:23.908
Radio silent for 30 minutes.

36:23.974 --> 36:27.025
Vulture Team is in the complex.

36:27.294 --> 36:29.482
Gonna try to pass word to Tiger Team.

36:29.507 --> 36:31.557
But Vulture has no comms. Over.

36:31.582 --> 36:33.704
Roger that. Make contact with Tiger Team.

36:33.729 --> 36:36.177
- Get me an exfil plan now.
- Roger.

36:36.202 --> 36:38.119
I'm looking for a rally point.

36:38.144 --> 36:40.478
We'll radio coordinates. Over.

36:40.503 --> 36:42.303
Any contact on the sonar?

36:42.328 --> 36:44.068
No, sir, but it won't take them long

36:44.093 --> 36:46.427
to figure out who blew up that radio relay.

36:56.113 --> 36:59.241
Friends, fellow immunes,

36:59.266 --> 37:02.429
my heart fills with
joy to see you all here.

37:02.454 --> 37:04.061
What a crowd!

37:04.929 --> 37:07.513
Woman: We love you, Sean!

37:07.538 --> 37:09.254
We love you, man!

37:09.279 --> 37:10.731
And I love you, too.

37:10.756 --> 37:13.544
Yes, I-I truly... I love all of you.

37:13.568 --> 37:16.374
And what a crowd.

37:16.594 --> 37:21.668
And more of you, more of
us arriving every hour.

37:21.693 --> 37:24.533
We expect a thousand by week's end.

37:24.558 --> 37:27.309
That's right. We're gonna
need a bigger ballroom.

37:27.334 --> 37:28.917
[Cheers and applause]

37:34.166 --> 37:36.554
With the 700 in St. Augustine,

37:36.579 --> 37:38.295
the 1,200 in Gainesville,

37:38.320 --> 37:40.830
and the nearly 6,000...

37:40.855 --> 37:45.453
That's right, 6,000... Across
the state in Clearwater,

37:45.479 --> 37:47.262
our ranks are growing,

37:47.287 --> 37:52.624
and we are spreading our
message across this great nation!

37:52.649 --> 37:56.568
And it all starts here with all of you...

37:56.593 --> 37:58.927
My beloved immunes.

37:58.952 --> 38:02.787
[Cheers and applause]

38:03.218 --> 38:05.718
Niels: At the safe zone in the mall,

38:05.841 --> 38:09.793
I found 320 immune to my disease.

38:09.986 --> 38:13.821
- That's bloody good, yeah?
- There are still...

38:13.857 --> 38:15.859
Many challenges before us...

38:15.884 --> 38:16.883
Creepy git.

38:16.908 --> 38:17.969
[Laughs]

38:17.994 --> 38:19.527
My brothers and sisters.

38:19.552 --> 38:23.367
There aren't many who have
not yet heard our message.

38:23.603 --> 38:26.687
That will change, my friends, because soon,

38:26.712 --> 38:31.414
we are going to New Orleans
to join other immunes

38:31.439 --> 38:34.781
so we can get our story
spread out across the country.

38:34.873 --> 38:40.109
But despite our many,
many successes so far,

38:40.134 --> 38:45.504
I still can't help feel
that I have failed you.

38:45.529 --> 38:50.253
- [Indistinct shouting]
- I come here as your humble messenger,

38:50.278 --> 38:52.862
spreading the gospel of the immunes.

38:52.887 --> 38:56.218
But if America is to rise again,

38:56.551 --> 38:59.711
it needs a true leader.

38:59.736 --> 39:01.859
- Sean, we have you!
- Lead us, Sean!

39:01.884 --> 39:03.664
No, no, no, no, not... not me. Not me.

39:03.689 --> 39:05.789
I... I come from a different land.

39:05.814 --> 39:09.016
American immunes need an American leader,

39:09.041 --> 39:13.399
someone who has our blood,
but your American spirit.

39:13.423 --> 39:15.028
Let's have a look at this.

39:18.826 --> 39:20.909
Reporter: <i> With Florida</i>
<i>reporting the first cases</i>

39:20.934 --> 39:23.129
<i>of the mysterious virus
that's sweeping Europe,</i>

39:23.154 --> 39:26.344
<i>secretary of housing and urban
development Jeffrey Michener</i>

39:26.369 --> 39:28.304
<i>landed in Tallahassee this morning</i>

39:28.329 --> 39:30.403
<i>as head of the U.S. response team.</i>

39:30.428 --> 39:32.294
Michener: <i> The information</i>
<i>we have right now,</i>

39:32.319 --> 39:33.979
<i>we seem to have contained the virus.</i>

39:34.004 --> 39:35.720
Reporter: <i>How did
the virus get here?</i>

39:35.745 --> 39:37.078
<i>As I said, we don't know</i>

39:37.103 --> 39:38.936
<i>how the virus landed on our shores,</i>

39:38.961 --> 39:40.710
<i>but we're doing everything we can</i>

39:40.735 --> 39:42.118
<i>to meet the challenge head-on.</i>

39:42.143 --> 39:43.977
<i>My office is doing everything we can</i>

39:44.002 --> 39:46.419
<i>to make sure that people are safe.</i>

39:46.444 --> 39:49.445
[Applause]

39:49.507 --> 39:54.427
Sean: Secretary Michener
shares our special gift.

39:54.452 --> 39:57.316
It's the reason he's alive
and here with us today

39:57.341 --> 39:59.317
while the rest of the U.S. government

39:59.342 --> 40:01.718
perished from this earth.

40:01.743 --> 40:05.295
Now, I have some news for you.

40:05.635 --> 40:09.218
According to the U.S. constitution,

40:09.243 --> 40:12.517
as secretary of housing
and urban development,

40:12.542 --> 40:16.043
Jeffrey Michener is number 12

40:16.068 --> 40:18.817
in the order of presidential succession.

40:18.842 --> 40:20.618
With the others all gone,

40:20.958 --> 40:26.317
well, Jeffrey Michener is your president.

40:26.342 --> 40:29.317
[Cheers and applause]

40:30.337 --> 40:34.118
You heard me right, and
when we get to New Orleans,

40:34.143 --> 40:36.817
we will install him in his rightful office,

40:36.842 --> 40:40.560
where he can create a cabinet,
take control of the military,

40:40.585 --> 40:45.255
and show the world that America is back!

40:45.280 --> 40:49.232
America has a new president!

40:49.257 --> 40:52.792
And he is one of us!

40:52.817 --> 40:55.718
[Cheers and applause]

40:59.432 --> 41:01.131
Sean, what the hell are you talking about?

41:01.156 --> 41:02.689
You didn't say anything about this.

41:02.846 --> 41:07.718
I told you, brother. I have a plan.

41:23.873 --> 41:26.540
